{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180912181710|859239162","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Mark_Walker_(North_Carolina_politician)","to":"Mark Walker (North Carolina politician)"}],"pages":{"43316202":{"pageid":43316202,"ns":0,"title":"Mark Walker (North Carolina politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-11T11:42:58Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Mark Walker\n|image       = Walker Official Photo 2017.jpg\n|state       = [[North Carolina]]\n|district    = {{ushr|NC|6|6th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2015\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Howard Coble]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1969|5|20}}\n|birth_place = [[Dothan, Alabama|Dothan]], [[Alabama]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Kelly Walker\n|education   = [[Trinity Baptist College]]<br>[[Piedmont International University|Piedmont International<br>University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n}}\n'''Bradley Mark Walker''' (born May 20, 1969) is an American politician and pastor from the state of [[North Carolina]]. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], Walker has represented [[North Carolina's 6th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 2015. In 2017, Walker was elected to head the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nWalker was born on May 20, 1969, in [[Dothan, Alabama]].<ref name=\"RCProfile\">[http://data.rollcall.com/members/52926 Rep. Mark Walker, R-N.C.: Member of the House (2nd term)], ''Roll Call'' (accessed January 30, 2017).</ref> His father was an [[Independent Baptist]] minister, and was the chaplain of a prison in Alabama.<ref name=\"wegmann\">{{cite web |url=http://dailysignal.com/2016/04/20/a-preacher-turned-lawmaker-and-his-new-campaign-to-win-the-old-war-on-poverty/ |title=A Preacher Turned Lawmaker and His New Campaign to Win the Old War on Poverty |last1=Wegmann |first1=Philip |date=April 20, 2016 |website=The Daily Signal |publisher=[[The Heritage Foundation]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWalker eventually attended [[Trinity Baptist College]] for a time before moving with his family to [[Houston, Texas]]. From there, Walker moved to the [[Piedmont Triad]]. He worked in business and finance for several years.<ref name=\"Vote Smart\">{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/146255/mark-walker#.V85XjZMrKRs | title=Mark Walker Bio}}</ref>  Walker eventually returned to college to pursue the ministry and attend Piedmont Baptist College, now [[Piedmont International University]], graduating with a B.A. in Biblical Studies. Walker was ordained in the [[Southern Baptist]] denomination.  His career in ministry began at Calvary Baptist Church in Winston-Salem. From there he has worked for and led churches in North Carolina and Florida. He has served as a worship pastor, executive pastor and lead pastor.\n\nIn 2008, Walker started with Lawndale Baptist Church in [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]] as its Pastor of Arts and Worship.<ref>[http://www.greensboro-nc.gov/modules/showdocument.aspx?documentid=18056 Biography and Resume at the City of Greensboro, North Carolina website]</ref> The church has a membership of several thousand congregants.<ref>Emily Cahn, [http://www.rollcall.com/news/home/religious-right-congress-jody-hice-georgia-2014#sthash.USzP0h8r.dpuf Megachurches Prove Mega-Influential in GOP Primaries], ''Roll Call'' (July 20, 2014).</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n;2014\nRepublican [[Howard Coble]] had represented the 6th district since 1985 when he announced his retirement at age 83. Coble supported [[Phil Berger Jr.]] in the May [[United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2014#District 6|primary election]] and Walker finished second, though in the [[runoff election]], Walker unexpectedly won 57%\u201344%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2014/07/15/baptist-minister-mark-walker-wins-republican-runoff-in-north-carolinas-6th-district/|title=Baptist minister Mark Walker wins Republican runoff in North Carolina\u2019s 6th District|last=Sullivan|first=Sean|date=July 15, 2014|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref> Most of Walker's election funding came from individual contributions, which he noted in his primary victory speech.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/politics-columns-blogs/under-the-dome/article10026368.html|title=How did Mark Walker blindside Phil Berger Jr.?|last=Jarvis|first=Craig|date=July 16, 2014|work=[[The News & Observer]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref> In the general election, Walker defeated Democrat attorney Laura Fjeld of [[Hillsborough, North Carolina|Hillsborough]]. \"I certainly do align with the Republican Party when it comes to traditional values,\" Walker said after the election, \"but even so, limited government is my heart and my nature and I think that says a lot about North Carolina and maybe we are still more red than purple.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfdd.org/story/walker-wins-6th-congressional-district-seat|title=Walker Wins 6th Congressional District Seat|last=Brown|first=Keri|date=November 5, 2014|work=[[WFDD]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref> He said that in his term he hoped to address poverty, immigration, and education issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfdd.org/story/walker-getting-things-done-congress-starts-local-community|title=Walker: Getting Things Done In Congress Starts With Local Community|last=Brown|first=Keri|date=November 18, 2014|work=[[WFDD]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n;2016\n\nWalker significantly outspent his opponent, Democrat Pete Glidewell, in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2016#District 6|2016 campaign]]; Walker's $818,000, about 40% from national [[political action committee]]s (PACs), was nine times what Glidewell had fundraised.<ref name=\"Glidewell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/elections/rep-mark-walker-wins-second-term-in-th-district/article_dd8bfd8c-a547-11e6-bce3-2b42d7adb52f.html|title=Rep. Mark Walker wins second term in 6th District|last=Newsom|first=John|date=November 8, 2016|work=[[News & Record]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref> All North Carolina incumbents retained their seats; in the 6th district, Walker received 59% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/election/article113423338.html|title=All North Carolina incumbents keep seats in Congress|last=Douglas|first=Anna|date=November 8, 2016|work=[[The News & Observer]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref> Neither Walker nor Glidewell won their home county in the election.<ref name=\"Glidewell\"/>\n\nDuring the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential election]], Walker called some of Republican nominee [[Donald Trump]]'s remarks \"morally reprehensible\"<ref name=\"DouglasVarying\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/election/article82849802.html|title=NC Republicans offer varying levels of support for Trump|last=Douglas|first=Anna|date=June 9, 2016|work=[[The News & Observer]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref> and condemned Trump's [[Donald Trump and Billy Bush recording|lewd remarks about women]] as \"vile.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/politics-columns-blogs/under-the-dome/article106930577.html|title=McCrory, Burr, others join condemnation of Trump|last=Jarvis|first=Craig|work=[[The News & Observer]]|date=October 8, 2016|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref> Nevertheless, Walker still backed Trump over his Democratic opponent, [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref name=\"DouglasVarying\"/> After the election, Walker expressed support for incoming president Trump on the issues of taxes and education, but said he could not stand behind Trump's statements about a registry tracking [[Islam in the United States|Muslim Americans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/article123104179.html|title=Meet the knuckleball pitcher in Congress who has redefined conservatives\u2019 strike zone|last=Douglas|first=Anna|date=December 27, 2016|work=[[The News & Observer]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n;2018\n\nWalker faced no primary challenger in [[United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina, 2018#District 6|2018]]. He is challenged in the general election by Democrat [[Ryan Watts (politician)|Ryan Watts]] of [[Burlington, North Carolina|Burlington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/north-carolina-house-district-6-primary-election|title=North Carolina Primary Election Results: Sixth House District|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 8, 2018|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref> On April 20, Walker's campaign raised $650,000 during a luncheon attended by [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Mike Pence]], the largest sum in U.S. House history, effectively doubling what Walker had previously raised.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/article209970629.html|title=An NC Republican says he just made campaign history|last=Specht|first=Paul A.|date=April 27, 2018|work=[[The News & Observer]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure and political views===\nWalker holds \"deeply conservative\" beliefs.<ref>Sherly Gay Stolberg, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/07/us/politics/as-power-in-congress-shifts-to-gop-lives-of-freshmen-in-transition.html As Power in Congress Shifts to G.O.P., Lives of Freshmen in Transition], ''New York Times'' (January 6, 2015).</ref> He is an avowed opponent of the [[Affordable Care Act]], and has led the conservative Republican Study Committee's efforts to repeal the [[Health care reform in the United States|health care reform]] legislation.<ref>MJ Lee & Deirdre Walsh, [http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/04/politics/conservatives-repeal-and-replace-obamacare-bill/ Conservative House Republicans unveil repeal and replace Obamacare bill], CNN (January 4, 2017).</ref> He has called for \"full repeal\" of the legislation, and criticized 2015 Republican-sponsored legislation that would repeal only part of the act.<ref>Alexander Bolton, [http://thehill.com/homenews/senate/260153-obamacare-repeal-teeters-in-senate ObamaCare repeal teeters in Senate], ''The Hill'' (November 16, 2015).</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Walker was one of only 33 Republican U.S. Representatives to vote \"no\" on a short-term stopgap funding measure that would appropriate millions of dollars in federal disaster relief spending in the wake of [[Hurricane Matthew]]. Walker said that he opposed such stopgap funding bills.<ref>Anna Douglas, [http://www.newsobserver.com/news/politics-government/article119919723.html Why a congressman voted against a bill with money for disaster relief in his district], ''News & Observer'' (December 9, 2016).</ref>\n\nWalker has led efforts to improve the Republican Party's outreach to [[African American]]s, and organized a February 2017 conference between the [[College president|presidents and chancellors]] of [[historically black colleges and universities]] (HBCUs) and Republican congressional leaders.<ref>William Douglas, [http://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/article129213204.html Will GOP\u2019s latest effort to reach out to black community last?],  ''News & Observer'' (January 30, 2017).</ref> He also worked with fellow Representative [[Alma Adams]], a Democrat from North Carolina, to start an internship program for students from HBCUs.<ref name=\"McPherson\">Lindsey McPherson, [http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/walker-wants-gop-lead-criminal-justice-immigration Walker Wants GOP to Lead on Criminal Justice, Immigration: Head of Republican Study Committee says new approach warranted], ''Roll Call'' (January 23, 2017).</ref> He is supportive of [[criminal justice reform]] initiatives, and has called for a shift in Republican approach to this issue.<ref name=\"McPherson\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Walker became co-chair of the Congressional Prayer Caucus.<ref>[http://www.courier-tribune.com/news/20170111/walker-co-chairs-prayer-caucus Walker co-chairs prayer caucus], ''Asheboro Courier-Tribune'' (January 11, 2017).</ref>\n\nWalker has played for the Republicans in the annual [[Congressional Baseball Game]], serving as [[Baseball pitcher|pitcher]] in the 2016 game.<ref>Alex Gangitano & Bridget Bowman, [http://www.rollcall.com/news/hoh/republicans-turn-back-democrats-thriller-8-7 Republicans Turn Back Democrats in Thriller, 8-7], ''Roll Call'' (June 23, 2016).</ref>\n\n====Republican Study Committee====\nIn 2016, Walker launched a campaign to become chairman of the Republican Study Committee (RSC), a faction of highly conservative Republicans. Walker defeated [[Andy Harris (politician)|Andy Harris]] of [[Maryland]] in the November 2016 election, becoming the youngest RSC chairman in history.<ref>.\n*Lindsey McPherson, [http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/walker-harris-running-republican-study-committee-chair#sthash.pUobbvL3.dpuf Walker, Harris Running for Republican Study Committee Chairmanship: Race pits freshman congressman against Freedom Caucus member], ''Roll Call'' (September 15, 2016).\n*Rachel Bade, [http://www.politico.com/story/2016/11/mark-walker-republican-study-committee-231553 Walker beats Harris for Republican Study Committee chair], ''Politico'' (November 17, 2016).</ref>\n\n====House Bill 2====\nWalker is a proponent of North Carolina's [[Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act]] (\"HB2\"), a controversial piece of legislation<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/article68401147.html |title=Understanding HB2: North Carolina\u2019s newest law solidifies state\u2019s role in defining discrimination |last1=Gordon |first1=Michael |last2=Price |first2=Mark S. | last3=Peralta |first3=Katie |date=March 26, 2015 |publisher= [[The Charlotte Observer]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> which was read, amended, passed and signed in a matter of hours on March 23, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncleg.net/gascripts/BillLookUp/BillLookUp.pl?Session=2015E2&BillID=HB2 |title=House Bill 2 / S.L. 2016-3 Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act. 2016 Second Extra Session |author=North Carolina General Assembly |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref> On March 28, 2016, as businesses and local governments began registering opposition to HB2, Walker tweeted, \"I'm growing weary of the big business and corporate bullying over HB2.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RepMarkWalker |number=714520443022082049 |date=March 28, 2016 |title=I'm growing weary of the big business and corporate bullying over HB2.}}</ref>  At a prayer breakfast on April 2016, Walker asserted that the Democrats had emphasized opposition to HB2 as \"part of a calculated strategy to retake control of the Senate, turn the state blue, and establish a base of support for the [2016] presidential election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dailysignal.com/2016/04/12/rep-mark-walker-liberals-exploiting-bathroom-bill-controversy-to-retake-north-carolina/ |title=Rep. Mark Walker: Liberals Exploiting Bathroom Bill Controversy for Political Gain |last1=Wegmann |first1=Philip |date=April 12, 2016 |website=[[The Daily Signal]] |publisher=[[The Heritage Foundation]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Remarks====\n\nWalker has made controversial statements that have brought him national attention; for example, in 2017 he described women colleagues publicly as \"[[Eye Candy (Visual appeal)|eye candy]]\".<ref name=twsCNN434>Caroline Kenny, September 26, 2017, CNN, [http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/26/politics/mark-walker-eye-candy-remarks/index.html RSC chair calls female colleagues 'eye candy' during remarks], Retrieved September 27, 2017, \"...The accomplished men and women of the RSC. And women. If it wasn't sexist, I would say the RSC eye candy, but we'll leave that out of the record....\"</ref><ref name=twsHeraldSun1>Brian Murphy and Lesley Clark, September 26, 2017, The Herald Sun, [http://www.heraldsun.com/news/politics-government/article175522086.html NC lawmaker calls Republican women \u2018eye candy\u2019 during press event], Retrieved September 27, 2017</ref> On May 15, 2017, Walker posted a tweet in which he criticized the construction of [[duck crossing|specially made ramps]] allowing ducks to get into and out of the [[US Capitol]] Reflecting Pool. In it, he called the move \"government waste.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RepMarkWalker |number=864223017135689728 |date=15 May 2017 |title=If it looks like a duck and walks like a duck, it must be government waste. }}</ref> The tweet was widely criticized on social media.<ref>{{cite web| last= Rozsa |first= Matthew |date= May 17, 2017 | url= http://www.salon.com/2017/05/17/gop-ducklings-washington-dc-mark-walters/| work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|title= So the GOP is anti-duckling now? | accessdate= May 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Greenwood|first=Max |date=May 16, 2017 |title=GOP rep decries Capitol duck ramp as 'government waste' |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/333705-gop-rep-decries-capitol-duck-ramp-as-government-waste |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=May 17, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nDuring his 2014 campaign, at a [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] forum in [[Rockingham County, North Carolina]], Walker was asked if military force was appropriate along the [[U.S.-Mexican border]]. He stated that the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] might be necessary to secure the border.<ref name=Record>{{cite news|title=War With Mexico? Of Course Not|url=http://www.news-record.com/news/walker-war-with-mexico-of-course-not/article_eeb349fa-3f9e-11e4-8089-001a4bcf6878.html|accessdate=September 19, 2014|publisher=News-Record|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> He added, \"...if you have foreigners who are sneaking in with drug cartels, to me that is a national threat, and if we got to go laser or blitz somebody.. I don\u2019t have a problem with that either.\" The moderator then asked if he had any qualms about starting a war with Mexico. Walker responded jokingly, \"Well, we did it before, if we need to do it again, I don't have a qualm about it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2014/09/18/4162234/republican-mark-walker-no-qualms.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 7, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110123131/http://www.newsobserver.com/2014/09/18/4162234/republican-mark-walker-no-qualms.html |archivedate=November 10, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wral.com/walker-he-doesn-t-have-a-qualm-about-war-with-mexico/13995217/ |title=Walker doesn't 'have a qualm' about war with Mexico |last1=Binker |first1=Mark |date=September 19, 2014 |website=WRAL.com |publisher=[[WRAL-TV]] |access-date=April 10, 2016}}</ref> Later, Walker met with the editors of the ''[[Greensboro News & Record]]'' to tell them, \"Being someone who is not a career politician, I\u2019ve learned there are different environments that are a little more heated in context. And when you walk into those by proxy, you have to be very concerned as well as being very upfront about what your positions are because you can be guided very easily.\"<ref name=\"killian\">{{cite web |url=http://www.greensboro.com/news/government/elections/will-the-real-mark-walker-step-up/article_3c5b3500-46c0-11e4-ba80-001a4bcf6878.html |title=Will the real Mark Walker step up? |last1=Killian |first1=Joe |date=September 27, 2014 |website=[[Greensboro News & Record]] |access-date=April 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Committee assignments==\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications|Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications]]\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation Security|Subcommittee on Transportation Security]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Information Technology]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on House Administration]]'''\n\n==Personal life==\nWalker is married to Kelly Sears, a [[nurse practitioner]].<ref>Kathy Chaffin, [http://elkintribune.com/news/1666/congressman-walker-tours-elkin Congressman Walker tours Elkin], ''Elkin Tribune'' (August 28, 2015).</ref> They have three children and live in [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]].<ref name=\"RCProfile\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.walker.house.gov Congressman Mark Walker] official House website\n* [http://www.walker4nc.com Mark Walker for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Mark_Walker_%5BR-6%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|bradleywalker}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=W000819 | votesmart=146255 | fec